_children.explanation:
The groups of persons can be made only in 2, 2, 1, 1<br><br>$$ \therefore $$ So the number of required ways is equal to number of ways to distribute the 6 distinct objects in group sizes 1, 1, 2 and 2<br><br>= $$\eqalign{
  &amp; {{6!} \over {{{(2!)}^2}{{(1!)}^2}(2!)(2!)}}(4!)  \cr 
  &amp;  = 360 \times 3 = 1080 \cr} $$

